body:
Every time I run my flutter application from IntelliJ, it loads an old, out of date version of my application from days ago.

It ends up producing weird issues. If I launch the debug version of the application, with a break point set, my application seems to be crashing and never getting to a point where I can refresh it. I have to launch into debug mode, refresh my application, and then set a break point before I can properly debug.

## Steps to Reproduce
1. Click the IntelliJ run button to run the flutter configuration
2. Watch an old version of the application (from days ago) get loaded into the android emulator.
3. Press hot reload, or app restart button, and now the app has all the changes from the past few days.

comment_data.body: Sorry to hear that @ScottPierce! I'm curious, If you `flutter run` the same app from the terminal does it have the same issue or not?

The current process for running the app is:
- create a snapshot of your code
- ship it over to the device
- start the app (from the snapshot)
- connect to the app via a debug connection
- ship all the Dart source over
- when we restart (a hot reload or a full restart) we use the source shipped over

It sounds like somehow we're failing to use the new snapshot when starting the app. Perhaps we're failing to write the new snapshot to the phone? An error like that should stop the launch process. Can you start up `adb logcat` from a command-line terminal and see if any errors show up for your next launch?

Confirmed that `flutter run` from the IntelliJ command line has the same issue.

The first time I run the app from a fresh emulator, I get an "MTP Host has stopped" error dialog popping up. I assumed initially that it was a genymotion process, but maybe the MTP process is owned by flutter?

@mit-mit I haven't been playing with flutter for a week or so, so I don't know.

@ScottPierce, I'm unable to repro this. I see some errors in your log that _look_ like issues with the file system (`appfuse mount`, `FileNotFound`, and `dlopen failed`). I don't know if these are non-issues or are related to why we can't write a new snapshot to the device.

I'm closing this issue, but we'll keep an eye out to see if we get any similar reports coming in.
